"Ponge J.-F., Jabiol B., Gégout J.-C.","Geology and climate conditions affect more humus forms than forest canopies at large scale in temperate forests",2011,"Geoderma","162","1-2",,"187","195",,,10.1016/j.geoderma.2011.02.003,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-79952901288&partnerID=40&md5=7d73cb0a3761d636f5fe474db9e3fbb7","Muséum National d'Histoire Naturelle, CNRS UMR 7179, 4 avenue du Petit-Château, 91800 Brunoy, France; AgroParisTech, INRA UMR 1092, Laboratoire d'Etude des Ressources Foret Bois (LERFoB), ENGREF, 14 rue Girardet, 54042 Nancy Cedex, France","Ponge, J.-F., Muséum National d'Histoire Naturelle, CNRS UMR 7179, 4 avenue du Petit-Château, 91800 Brunoy, France; Jabiol, B., AgroParisTech, INRA UMR 1092, Laboratoire d'Etude des Ressources Foret Bois (LERFoB), ENGREF, 14 rue Girardet, 54042 Nancy Cedex, France; Gégout, J.-C., AgroParisTech, INRA UMR 1092, Laboratoire d'Etude des Ressources Foret Bois (LERFoB), ENGREF, 14 rue Girardet, 54042 Nancy Cedex, France","We investigated by linear gradient analysis (RDA) the relationships between forest humus forms (9 humus forms and the Humus Index) and 148 variables describing geology, climate, soil type, geography and the floristic composition of forest canopies, using 3441 plots of the EcoPlant database covering the whole French territory. Among these variables, geology (alkaline vs acidic substrate) and climate (warm/dry vs cold/rainy) were the major determinants of humus forms, scaling mull humus forms from eumull to dysmull and opposing them to mor/moder, while the contribution of tree canopies was negligible. This trend was verified by partial RDA with environment or abundance of tree species from forest canopy as co-factors. The original position of amphi was confirmed: it was the only humus form not included in the gradient of increasing biological activity ordinated according to climate and geology. Results and possible forecasts of humus forms according to global warming were discussed to the light of existing knowledge. © 2011 Elsevier B.V.","Climate; EcoPlant database; Humus form; Humus Index; Parent rock; Soil type","Climate; EcoPlant database; Humus form; Humus Index; Parent rock; Soil type; Database systems; Forestry; Geology; Global warming; Soils; abundance; bioactivity; climate conditions; database; floristics; forest canopy; forest soil; global warming; humus; parent material; soil type; temperate forest; Data Bases; Forest Canopy; Forestry; Geology; Humus; Plants; Rock; Soil; France",,,,,,"Aerts, R., Climate, leaf litter chemistry and leaf litter decomposition in terrestrial ecosystems: a triangular relationship (1997) Oikos, 79, pp. 439-449; (2009) Référentiel Pédologique 2008, coordinated by D. Baize and C.M. Girard, , Quae, Paris, France, AFES; Arp, P.A., Krause, H.H., The forest floor: lateral variability as revealed by systematic sampling (1984) Can. J. Soil Sci., 64, pp. 423-437; Aubert, M., Bureau, F., Alard, D., Bardat, J., Effect of tree mixture on the humic epipedon and vegetation diversity in managed beech forests (Normandy, France) (2004) Can. J. For. Res., 34, pp. 233-248; Aubert, M., Margerie, P., Ernoult, A., Decaëns, T., Bureau, F., Variability and heterogeneity of humus forms at stand level: comparison between pure beech and mixed beech-hornbeam forest (2006) Ann. For. Sci., 63, pp. 177-188; Augusto, L., Dupouey, J.L., Ranger, J., Effects of tree species on understory vegetation and environmental conditions in temperate forests (2003) Ann. For. Sci., 60, pp. 823-831; Bednorz, F., Reichstein, M., Broll, G., Holtmeier, F.K., Urfer, W., Humus forms in the forest-alpine tundra ecotone at Stillberg (Dischmatal, Switzerland): spatial heterogeneity and classification (2000) Arct. Antarct. Alp. Res., 32, pp. 21-29; Beisner, B.E., Haydon, D.T., Cuddington, K., Alternative stable states in ecology (2003) Front. Ecol. Environ., 1, pp. 376-382; Bernier, N., Altitudinal changes in humus form dynamics in a spruce forest at the montane 